c9526950d99a"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Building a classifier in an unsupervised way", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7811964520408287`*^9, 3.7811964568004894`*^9}, {
   3.7811964955836935`*^9, 3.7811965166328487`*^9}, 
   3.78184143661466*^9},ExpressionUUID->"c661ac66-01ab-42b6-a763-\
6fd5650d2e75"],

Cell["\<\
For classification, we use data from known classes. Classes are normally \
defined by humans (e.g. species of iris flowers, the type of animal, etc). Is \
in this sense that classification is a supervised machine learning task \
(humans are supervising...).

Given a dataset, however, one could do classification in a completely \
unsupervised way by
(i) Find clusters in the data
(ii) Define a class based on each cluster. 
(iii) Train a classifier using the data labeled by the clusters. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.781841123753993*^9, 3.781841186296835*^9}, {
  3.781841231610895*^9, 3.7818413808437805`*^9}, {3.7818414420050373`*^9, 
  3.781841524172123*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"192e93c9-3e2a-4542-a24e-\
3592cb9815e9"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["ClusterClassify function", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.781841628418268*^9, 
  3.7818416378600817`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"703947b5-4587-4f7b-99ff-\
24ede56cd825"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In Mathematica, this can be achieved with the ",
 StyleBox["ClusterClassify", "CodeText"],
 " function which generates a ",
 StyleBox["ClassifierFunction[\[Ellipsis]]", "CodeText"],
 " by partitioning data into clusters of similar elements.\n\nLet us consider \
the data set used at the beginning of this section."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7818415834673243`*^9, 3.7818416904638014`*^9}, {
  3.7818418561509595`*^9, 
  3.781841858806068*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"4db1ce37-0c8b-4e2e-a357-\
a8095c1470ba"],

