Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["How good is the classification?", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7818422855588417`*^9, 
  3.7818422928300743`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"848e4394-7fc2-42f2-93c2-\
8c07849a7ef7"],

Cell["\<\
If we take cluster1 and cluster2 as the true classification (e.g. true \
species determined by humans perhaps using more features), how good is \
unsupervised classification?

There are several measures to evaluate the results.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.781842297134047*^9, 
  3.7818423895195684`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"38fa67e1-36c5-42d6-b37c-\
eda5adae7f9a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Purity", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.781842575558887*^9, 
  3.7818425766677103`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"35b47448-7ce5-4c1a-b576-\
c6aa2bb5dafe"],

Cell["\<\
Purity is perhaps the most basic measure to evaluate the \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]unsupervised\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] classifier. For \
each cluster, count the number of data points from the most common class in \
said cluster. Now take the sum over all clusters and divide by the total \
number of data points.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.7818425895056887`*^9, {3.7818434424460735`*^9, 
   3.7818434763234253`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1e0218bc-44bf-4ca8-8dac-\
e6b81022bfc5"],

Cell["For the example studied above, one can proceed as follows:", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.7818432691573067`*^9, 3.7818432866863976`*^9}, {
  3.781878807029683*^9, 
  3.7818788179312706`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5160120b-926e-4659-b899-\
e071e1542588"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The most common class in the true class cluster1 is", "Item",
